</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#C5C5BA><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub12.ezboard.com/uaalek.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Aalek</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Torvonnite</span><br>  Posts: 53<br> <font color=#122950>(10/2/01 11:32:20 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Yeah... so?</span><hr size=1> The logical end result of FCFS is that as more and more guilds become capable of killing these contested/desired mobs, things will in fact degenerate into a race-to-the-mob effect, or guilds parking folks at spawn points for hours on end waiting for spawns.<br>
<br>
Another logical result would be that the most powerful guilds will dominate all of the high end mobs and the less powerful guilds will get whatever scraps are left over.  Even guilds who have the people and the skills but can't have everyone online 24/7 will only get what the larger guilds don't want.<br>
<br>
With a reservation system the guilds capable of killing a mob can take turns in a rotation and even plan ahead as to when they need to gather their forces for the task.  With FCFS, only guilds who are up to the task on a moments notice will have a reasonable shot at the most desired mobs.<br>
<br>
